After the kubeadm init command finishes on the control plane, it will output a join command. Copy that command and run it with sudo on both Worker Nodes. It looks like this:

Bash
-----------------------------------------------------------------
token are in cont plan:::---------
----------------------------------------------------------
sudo kubeadm join <control-plane-ip>:6443 --token <token> \
    --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:<hash>


It looks like you have two missing system configurations on your worker nodes. Also, the last part of your hash was cut off into a new line, which caused the "command not found" error.

Run these commands on both worker nodes to fix the preflight errors:

1. Install Conntrack
Kubernetes requires conntrack for networking and service routing.

Bash
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y conntrack
2. Enable IP Forwarding
This allows the node to route traffic correctly between pods.

Bash
# Enable it immediately
sudo sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1

# Make it persistent across reboots
echo "net.ipv4.ip_forward=1" | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
3. Run the Join Command Again
Make sure you paste the command as one single line. Your previous attempt split the hash ...000 and 5106... onto two lines.

Corrected Command:

Bash
sudo kubeadm join 172.31.27.68:6443 --token wwemfz.xpjjfd3dkqpov8tw --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:18ee2785e96d3a2d1a551e01003e510310920005106bcb4568fd2750500e52a0
Note: If you still get a "Connection Refused" or timeout error, ensure your Control Plane Security Group in AWS allows inbound traffic on port 6443 from your worker nodes' private IP addresses.
